## N-well Diode
- Placing an n-well in the p-substrate forms a diode 
   - The DC characteristics of the diode are given by
     - $I_{D} = I_{S}(e^{\frac{Vd}{nV_{T}}}-1)$
- The scale current is related in SPICE by an area factor
### Well process problems
-  When implanting the n-well for an n-well process
   the substrate must be *counter-doped*
- Meaning that the p-substrate must have n-type dopants added until its concentration changes from p-type to n-type
 - The problem with counter-doping is the p-substrate acceptor atoms becomes ionized (*electrons fall out of holes*)
- This increases scattering and reduces mobility 

- A PMOS device fabricated in an n-well is slower than a PMOS device in a p-well process
#### The Fix $\uparrow$ (*Twin Well Process*)
- In order to reduce excessive doping effects
   - Using a lighter doped substrate the amount of counter doping is reduced
- Note that an intrinsic silicon substrate isn't used in order to control the doping at such low levels
   
